Immunoglobulin superfamily member 8 maintains myeloid leukemia stem cells through inhibition of ß-catenin degradation.
At a molecular level, we found that activation of ß-catenin in LSCs depends on Igsf8, which promotes the association of FZD4 with its co-receptor LRP6 in the presence of Igsf8. Similarly, IGSF8 inhibition blocks the colony-forming ability of LSCs and improves the survival of recipients in xenograft models of myeloid leukemia. Collectively, these data indicate strong genetic evidence identifying Igsf8 as a key regulator of myeloid leukemia and the possibility that targeting IGSF8 may serve as a new therapeutic approach against myeloid leukemia.
